es to preaching and print, as the unique potential for sermons to influence both popular and elite audiences became clear. As well as contributing to our understanding of preaching during the Civil Wars therefore, this book engages with recent debates about the nature of royalism in seventeenth-century England.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aRoyalistszGreat BritainxHistoryy17th century. 0aSermonszGreat BritainxHistoryy17th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / Stuart Era (1603-1714).2bisacsh  aCensorship.  aCharles I.  aCharles II.  aChurch of England.  aCourt Culture.  aEnglish Revolution.  aPopular Politics.  aPreaching.  aPrint Culture.  aRoyalism.1 aWhite, William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152616471140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526164711423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526164711/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles